    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1947-08-16T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1947-08-16T12:00:00-05:00" n="832"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d832">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">501.BC/8–1647: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Acting United States Representative at the United Nations</hi>
                        (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">restricted</hi>
                        <lb/>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">us urgent</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1947-08-16T13:00:00-04:00"
                            >August 16, 1947—1 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>356. If Netherlands should request <gloss target="#t_ICJ1">ICJ</gloss>
                    consideration problem of <gloss target="#t_SC1">SC</gloss> jurisdiction in
                    Indonesian question, Dept views are as follows: <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>US believes <gloss target="#t_SC1">SC</gloss> should not hesitate to
                            refer to <gloss target="#t_ICJ1">ICJ</gloss> questions on which <gloss
                                target="#t_SC1">SC</gloss> desires advisory opinions. Subject to
                            considerations set forth below, US will support <gloss target="#t_SC1"
                                >SC</gloss>’s asking advisory opinion of <gloss target="#t_ICJ1"
                                >ICJ</gloss> re <gloss target="#t_SC1">SC</gloss>’s jurisdiction in
                            Indonesian question, assuming, of course, text of resolution requesting
                            opinion is satisfactory. However, US considers principle important that
                                <gloss target="#t_SC1">SC</gloss> remain free, while <gloss
                                target="#t_ICJ1">ICJ</gloss> is deliberating, to take such further
                            action in conformity with Charter as <gloss target="#t_SC1">SC</gloss>
                            may determine necessary to maintain international peace.</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>Presumably consideration of Australian resolution and amendments
                            suggested in <gloss target="#t_Deptel1">Deptel</gloss> 347 of August 13
                            will precede consideration of question of reference to <gloss
                                target="#t_ICJ1">ICJ</gloss>. Any attempt to change order of <gloss
                                target="#t_SC1">SC</gloss>
                            <pb facs="1047" n="1033" xml:id="pg_1033"/> consideration these two
                            questions would imply attempt to divert or preclude consideration of
                            Australian proposal. Therefore, in Dept’s view, US should not support
                            such attempt.</item>
                        <label>3.</label>
                        <item>Obviously terms of reference to <gloss target="#t_ICJ1">ICJ</gloss>
                            must be precise. Therefore, Dept considers that you should take position
                            that vote on resolution to refer matter to <gloss target="#t_ICJ1"
                                >ICJ</gloss> should not be taken until <gloss target="#t_SC1"
                                >SC</gloss> members have had full opportunity to study draft
                            resolution.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lovett</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
